The variables are very diverse. They must be normalized. Insulin is measured in UI/mL, its maximum is more than 700 in the dataset. Other variables like 'BMI' have a lower interquartile range.

It is therefore necessary to normalize the data to homogenize the scales between the variables.

On this graph, we can see the distribution of data y. 1 corresponds to a patient who is diabetic and -1 who is not.

It can be noted that there are more non-diabetic patients, which is reassuring. However, this dataset is not necessarily representative of the population. In France, 1 person out of 10 has diabetes, according to this site: http://ceed-diabete.org/fr/le-diabete/les-chiffres/.

In [9]:
sns.pairplot(pd.DataFrame(data, columns=np.append(varnames_pima,'y')), hue='y', palette="tab10")
Out[9]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x7fcccd6c2d60>

Thanks to this pairplot between all the variables, we can try to predict which variables can help us to predict diabete. For this, we put colors according to the real classes (diabetes and non-diabetes).

We can then try to locate the scatter plot where the two classes are clearly separable. For example the variable glucose seems to be very important. If we look at any variable as a function of glucose, the two colors are clearly separated. This indicates that looking at a patient's glucose level can help a lot to conclude about the person's diabetes.

On the diagonal, we can see the distribution of each variable in a histogram. With all this informations we can make these assumptions:

  • Glucose: the rate would be higher in people with diabetes
  • Insuline and BMI: A rate also more important but it is less visible than for glucose
  • Skin thickness: seems to well separate our two classes.
  • Other : little or no visible influence

For a medical vision, I did some research and asked some health professionals. The main factor of diabetes is glucose. A doctor concludes about a patient's diabetes by looking at his fasting glucose level and over time. A diabetic patient has hyperglycemia. So it is not surprising to see in our dataset that sugar has a very important place in predicting diabetes. However, the other variables are also (secondary) factors of Diabetes.

  • Insulin : Hormone that lowers blood sugar.
  • BMI : body mass index, according to my research people with diabetes sometimes have a higher BMI.

We see that now all the variables have been normalized. The insulin variable has many outliers. We can also compare the ranges between the variables. Glucose has the highest range.

It is a problem to not have the same scaling and variances. Indeed, without normalizer we could not compare the variables. In addition, it prevents an algorithm from valuing one variable over another because it has higher values.

I.2- Bayesian decision and linear classification¶

Let's create a dataframe in order to store the performance mesures of our algorithms.

In [17]:
import pandas as pd
from tabulate import tabulate
 
data = {'Algorithm':[],
        
        'Accuracy (test set)': [],
        'AUC (test set)':[]
       }
 
df_pima = pd.DataFrame(data)

def print_all_measures_pima():
    print(tabulate(round(df_pima, 2), headers='keys', tablefmt='pretty',showindex=False))
In [18]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, roc_auc_score

def print_performance_on_test_pima(clf, df ,algorithm_name_for_df_save=''):
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y1_test, clf.predict(x1_test))
    auc      = roc_auc_score(y1_test, clf.predict_proba(x1_test)[:,1])
    print('Accuracy on test = ', accuracy)
    print('AUC on test      = ', auc)
    
    if len(algorithm_name_for_df_save) > 0:
        df = df.append({'Algorithm' : algorithm_name_for_df_save, 
                
                'Accuracy (test set)' : accuracy, 
                'AUC (test set)' : auc
               }, ignore_index=True)
        return df

Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)¶

LDA is a linear classifier.

In [19]:
from sklearn.discriminant_analysis import LinearDiscriminantAnalysis
In [20]:
LDA = LinearDiscriminantAnalysis()
LDA.fit(x1_train, y1_train)
df_pima = print_performance_on_test_pima(LDA, df_pima,'LDA default')

Accuracy on test =  0.8117359413202934
AUC on test      =  0.8619680560113773

We can see that even with the default settings we get very good results.

In [21]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
param_grid = {'solver' : ['lsqr', 'eigen'],
             'shrinkage' : np.linspace(0,1,100)}
grid_search_LDA = GridSearchCV(LDA, param_grid=param_grid,scoring='roc_auc')
no_display = grid_search_LDA.fit(x1_train, y1_train)
Note: I decided to run all my GridGearch with the AUC score so I can get a little difference in the results.

81% of patients are well classified. This is a good result, changing the parameters did not greatly improve the results. But the choice of a linear classifier seems to be adequate for this problem.

The highest weight was placed on glucose. This seems to be a very good choice from a medical point of view. The second one was placed on BMI which also seems to be consistent.

An other important weight is observed for pregancies and Age. For age, the older you get, the more likely you are to eat bad things or to become overweight and therefore diabetic. So it can make sense. But for pregnancies I see no link with diabetes. Maybe there is a medical link that I don't know about, or maybe the algorithm has detected a link in the dataset that doesn't exist in real life.

In [25]:
pl.hist(LDA.predict_proba(x1_test)[y1_test==1,1], label='y1_test = 1', alpha=0.5)
pl.hist(LDA.predict_proba(x1_test)[y1_test==-1,1], label='y1_test = -1', alpha=0.5)
pl.title('Separability of the sample in the predicted score space / test set')
fig = pl.legend()

This graph is interesting. You can see the distribution of the probability returned by LDA. This distribution is cut in two according to the patients who really have diabetes and those who do not.

Knowing that the algorithm chooses the categorial prediction with the probability threshold of 0.5, this graph allows to visualize the false predictions. If the algorithm had been perfect, the two histograms would not touch. We can even say that the false negative rate looks important, it's very bad for a medical application of this type. We will analyze this problem later in the lab.

Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)¶

QDA is a classifier with a quadratic decision boundary, Let's see if we can have better results than LDA.

In [27]:

The default parameters give much worse results than LDA.

In [29]:

Grid Search returns the best value for the reg_param parameter.

In [31]:

QDA.fit(x1_train, y1_train)
df_pima = print_performance_on_test_pima(QDA, df_pima,'QDA')

Accuracy on test =  0.7995110024449877
AUC on test      =  0.8626517886445684

Thanks to the change of the parameter, we manage to obtain a much more correct performance.

In [32]:

pl.title('Separability of the sample in the predicted score space / test set')
fig = pl.legend()

The performance indices have decreased compared to LDA but we have the impression that the false negative rate is lower. For medical use, it would be necessary to know whether a physician would prefer to have a lower accuracy or a lower false negative rate.

In [43]:
pl.hist(LR.predict_proba(x1_test)[y1_test==1,1], label='y1_test==1', alpha=0.5)

The number of false negatives seems to be much higher than the previous algorithms. On the other hand the number of false positives is reduced.

Thanks to this dataset, we can see that there is not only the performance index (like accuracy) to evaluate an algortihme. Depending on the problem to solve, there are many other indicators that can be taken into account. For this problem, the false negative indicator is extremely important, I would even say more important than the accuracy.

In [80]:
disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=confusion_matrix(y1_test, LR.predict(x1_test)),
                              display_labels=LR.classes_)
disp.plot()
Out[80]:
<sklearn.metrics._plot.confusion_matrix.ConfusionMatrixDisplay at 0x7fccd2ed7520>

Here is the confusion Matrix. With this matrix we can have easily access to the number of false negative (FN) and false positive(FP). From left to rigth and top to bottom we have, TN, FP, FN and TP.

In our case the false positive rate is not very important. If the algorithm is wrong, says that a patient is positive, there will be additional tests to verify this. On the other hand, if the algorithm says that a patient is negative when he is positive, the patient will go home believing that he is healthy. For each case of detection of a disease in the medical environment (e.g. COVID) the FNR must be as low as possible.

With a linear algorithm you can do this kind of customization, with a non linear one it's more difficult.

Here there are 52 false negative patients with the logistic regression algorithm. Let's transform this value into a rate to realize its importance.

In [81]:
def FNR(confusion_matrix):
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix.ravel()
    return fn/(fn+tp)

def FPR(confusion_matrix):
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix.ravel()
    return fp/(fp+tn)

FNR(confusion_matrix(y1_test, LR.predict(x1_test)))
Out[81]:
0.3939393939393939

This value is important, too in a case of disease detection. The lab proposes that we modify the intercept of the linear function to lower this rate. Let's test it.

In [82]:
LR.intercept_
Out[82]:
array([-0.49680147])
In [83]:
intercept_list = np.linspace(-3,1, 100)
In [84]:
FNR_list = []
FPR_list = []
accuracy_list = []
LR = LogisticRegression(C=grid_search_LR.best_params_['C'], 
                        penalty=grid_search_LR.best_params_['penalty'], 
                        solver=grid_search_LR.best_params_['solver'])
LR.fit(x1_train, y1_train)
for intercept in intercept_list:
    LR.intercept_ = intercept
    FNR_list.append(FNR(confusion_matrix(y1_test, LR.predict(x1_test))))
    FPR_list.append(FPR(confusion_matrix(y1_test, LR.predict(x1_test))))
    accuracy_list.append(accuracy_score(y1_test, LR.predict(x1_test)))
fig = pl.subplots(1, figsize=(10,7))
pl.plot(intercept_list,FNR_list, label='FNR')
pl.plot(intercept_list,FPR_list, label='FPR')
pl.plot(intercept_list,accuracy_list, label='Accuracy')
pl.axvline(x=-0.49679099, c='r')
pl.legend()
pl.xlabel('Intercept Value')
pl.ylabel('FN AND FP RATE')
pl.grid()
FNR_list = np.array(FNR_list)

In red we can see the original value of the intercept, which correspond to an FNR of 0.39.

We see that if we increase the value of the intercept, we can decrease the value of the FNR. This is what we are interested in. But this will also increase the value of the FPR. You have to find the right balance depending on the problem.

I also added the global accuracy on the graph. We notice that SKlearn probably chose the value of the intercept by taking the maximum value of the accuracy, without taking into account the FN and FP rates, it seems logical.

We will now take the value of the intercept which allows to have the FNR lower than 0.1 but without increasing too much the FPR:

In [85]:
np.where(FNR_list<0.1)
Out[85]:
(array([81, 82, 83, 84, 85, 86, 87, 88, 89, 90, 91, 92, 93, 94, 95, 96, 97,
        98, 99]),)

Here, we find the indices that allow us to have the FNR below 0.1. Let's take the lowest of this list in order to not loose so much in accuracy and not to increase the FNR too much.

In [86]:
LR.intercept_ = intercept_list[np.where(FNR_list<0.1)[0][0]] # we modify the intercept
In [87]:
FNR(confusion_matrix(y1_test, LR.predict(x1_test)))
Out[87]:
0.09848484848484848

The FNR is well below 0.1 as desired.

def print_performance_on_test_mnist(clf, df ,algorithm_name_for_df_save=''):
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y2_test, clf.predict(x2_test))
    print('Accuracy on test = ', accuracy)
    
    if len(algorithm_name_for_df_save) > 0:
        df = df.append({'Algorithm' : algorithm_name_for_df_save, 
                
                'Accuracy (test set)' : accuracy
               }, ignore_index=True)
        return df

  • Then there are 1 miss-predicted in 7, which is for me the most logical missclassification. Indeed as a human being it can be easier to make a mistake between a 7 and a 1 than between an 8 and a 1.

Looking at the classified miss samples, we can say :

  • Almost all misclassifieds have quite special forms, it is not illogical that they have been mispredicted.
  • The 8 predicted in 1 are very thin 8.
  • The 1 with rounding borders are transformed into 7.
  • The very thick 1 are transformed into 8.

Looking at these examples, I would say that the limitation of the algorithm is that it looks at pixels by pixels, it does not look at the whole image. A CNN might be more efficient on weird written numbers, it would look at the patterns that correspond to a given class like a human being would.

model.add(Conv2D(nb_filters, kernel_size=kernel_size, input_shape=(img_rows, img_cols, nb_channels), activation='relu',strides=(1, 1) , name='Conv1', padding='same'))
model.add(Conv2D(nb_filters, kernel_size=kernel_size, input_shape=(img_rows, img_cols,n_h_1),activation='relu',strides=(1, 1) , name='Conv2', padding='same'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2),strides=(2, 2), name='MaxPool1'))
model.add(Flatten(name='Flatten1'))
model.add(Dense(y2_train_cnn.shape[1], activation='softmax',name='Dense1'))

The use of a CNN allows to be much more robust to adversarial sampling. With a coefficient of 0.5, we can hardly distinguish the image with the naked eye, the algorithm keeps an accuracy of 0.5 on 1000 samples.

However, it is important to keep in mind that we are dealing with very simple images and that it is always possible to create adversarial samples specific to a CNN.

Conclusion¶

I really enjoyed working on this lab and all the others. From this LAB I will remember that it is not always the accuracy or the performance indicators that count. Other factors are also important like the false negative rate or the resistance to adversarial samples.

I will also remember that even if sklearn seems at first sight to be like a magic black box that allows you to obtain results very quickly, you have to remain curious about its functioning. First by trying to find optimal parameters and then by knowing that it is possible to act on other more hidden parameters such as the intercept.

Even if this course is over, I will continue to practice as much as possible because I am very interested about this discipline. I heard about the kaggle website which can be a good tool for regular training with its competitions. But I think the problem with this site is that you are only rated on the accuracy rendered by your algorithm. Nevertheless, it surely allows to gain experience.

I am this year in apprenticeship and I work on the Google cloud tools. So in parallel to the course I was interested in the existing cloud tools related to machine learning, there are many. I can mention BigQuey ML, Vertex AI, and others. So I will have the opportunity to learn these tools in more detail during the year.
